Let me describe to you all the easiest way of dealing with shitposters that requires the least amount of effort.

First, you need 4chan X. It is a browser extension that makes browsing 4chan a lot better and adds various features.
Among those are self-moderation tools. 4chan X is available for pretty much any browser and device.

Second, you need to apply the following settings to 4chanX in the main menu:
enable "Filter"
enable "Recursive Hiding"
enable "Reply Hiding Buttons"
disable "Stubs"

Third, you will see a [-] icon next to every post now.
Once you click that icon the post next to it gets hidden as well as every single post replying to it.
If you hide a patient zero of shitstorm you will remain unaware of what is going on, since you won't see any of it and that includes samefagging and idiots who took the bait.
Any additional shitposts can be taken care of with the same procedure and it takes even less effort than the lowest effort shitpost.

And now you can browse a clean and undiluted thread.

here's some ideas/advice
>do not include game mechanics/overlay in the world since that is the thing very very overdone even in the genre
>being the chosen hero or whatever and given bullshit OP powers is pretty boring at this point and just devolves into generic power fantasy trope
>just because you know modern science/tech doesn't mean you can actually peddle it since you're a nobody and why would they listen to you
>also remember galileo was nearly lynched by the church for saying the sun was the center of ours universe and not the Earth
>the most interesting parts of fantasy worlds is how they work and the rules they go by and how the different races/species interact
>do try not to just copy+paste tolkien when it comes fantasy races and how they act
a very important one
>ask yourself if there's actually anything to gain by having it be an isekai and not just a regular fantasy story

Whatever there is that's more in depth than just "world with anthros, humans exists, some humans from our all human world end up there, that world has a government agency to help humans from our world adjust to life in their world."
What are the size differences between different anthros and humans? Are they all relatively human sized? Are they within a foot or two of human (like mice anthros being in the four foot range while bear anthros are within the seven foot range)?
Is their world just an altered version of ours? Are the continents the same? Are the countries the same? Is their history the same? (roughly speaking for the last two)
How do the different anthros interact with each other and humans? Do they interact differently with humans naturally in their world versus those from our world? How do humans naturally from their world interact with humans from our world?
What else does the government do? Do they experiment on humans from our world upon finding them, then make them forget they were experimented on? How much is the government studying the phenomena? Are they trying to see if there is a way to open up a permanent link between worlds (regardless of if it is actually possible)? How much does the bureaucratic side of it hold the hands of the humans that end up there? Is it just a program to get them off their feet or do they have to constantly deal with this special government agency for the rest of their lives?
How animalistic are the anthros (not counting size)? Do they retain the instinctual fear of species that would've been predators of them? Do they have Jacobson's organs and the ability to communicate through smells? Are their hands very human like, just being covered in fur and having claws, or are they a sort of in between blend? Are they all plantigrade or do they retain their proper leg form? Do they retain a relative amount of their body structure (i.e. how wolves stand much taller than humans but weigh much less)?
And plenty more.

A very old general (for /trash/, at least) that was a sort of predecessor to /adhg/. It came before /hmofa/, but was very broad, allowing any sort of pairing. If you're going to "educate" anyone on isekai, keep your personal editorial notes out of it. Use google if you don't actually know what it is.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isekai
https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TrappedInAnotherWorld

It's a very broad genre, even if some specific interpretations irritate you. Literally, someone coming from another world into ours is isekai. It doesn't even have to involve our own world at all, it (technically) can be someone from any world that ends up in another. Time travel is also isekai, to a large extent.

Yeah, your comments about irritating tropes are valid opinions about how some isekai stories are developed, but don't pretend that those are the only stories or the majority of stories.

/hmofa/ requires isekai to construct and develop most themes for /hmofa/. Doesn't matter if someone from our world goes to another or someone from another world comes to ours, it's isekai. The only stories that aren't don't really involve our world at all, or they're some alternate timeline/universe with no crossover.

Bitch about isekai all you want, or specific tropes you hate, but /hmofa/ would have maybe 10% or even 5% of it;s content without it. It's not bad thing in and of itself, it can be a bad thing depending on how it's executed.

Anonymous Fri 23 Apr 2021 13:48:37 No.38126321 Report
Quoted By: >>38126548 >>38126580
>>38125726
>BNA as an isekai kind of stretches the genre to a point where Lord of the Rings can be considered an isekai
BNA is pretty legit as an isekai. It checks all the boxes. TYhe 'requirement' that it be a physically different world is a bit artificial. Anima City is the different world.

Yes, this is an abstraction of the isekai genre, but only in that one aspect. It's a pretty creative way to pull it off. Avoids all the messy handwavium pseudophysics and mumbomagicjumbo of how did the main characters get from one world to another.

LotR is another level of stretch. I get why you used that example, but there is a line crossed between those examples. Getting suddenly physically transformed for unknown reasons and thrown into an alien society without resources or any knowledge of said society is the essence of isekai. The LotR route is more discovery of the world you live in with a lot of mentoring and guidance. It's more of an advanced tourism story.

The real point here, though, is how it relates to /hmofa/. All I was trying to say is that isekai is fully legit plot mechanism for /hmofa/ stories, a difficult one to avoid. Embrace it and apply extra creativity and it's fine. No need to avoid it for the sake of avoiding it.

Anonymous Fri 23 Apr 2021 14:30:03 No.38126785 Report
Quoted By: >>38126884
>>38126580
Depending on how the stories are constructed and presented, they COULD be isekai. Not necessarily so.

Suppose a human returns to Earth without even knowing it's Earth and has to rediscover it as if it's an alien world. That would meet the criteria, whereas if the main characters knew what they were returning to and had other knowledge, it probably wouldn't.

How the main characters perceive what hey are going through controls much of the determination. Utawarerumono is a good example here: The main has memory loss and has no idea he's still on his planet of origin. As well as far out of his time. The story qualifies as isekai as far as he experiences it. Gaining his memory back in the conclusion doesn't change the story of what he went through prior to that.

How the author constructs & presents plus how the characters live the experience are the primary determining factors.
